post_text:
NC Governor Roy Cooper issued Executive Order 163 on September 1. That order includes a change in the requirement for face coverings. It states that, based on the recommendation from the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, face shields will no longer meet the requirements for face coverings. Beginning at 5 p.m. September 4, Carteret County Public School System students and employees must wear a face covering that meets the CDC's guidelines unless they have requested and received an accommodation through their principal or director. Face coverings can be made of a variety of synthetic and natural fabrics and, ideally, have two or more layers. Face coverings can be masks, surgical masks or gaiters.
Remember the three Ws: WEAR a cloth mask over your nose and mouth; WAIT six feet apart; and WASH your hands or use hand sanitizer. Let's stay healthy, safe and CarteretStrong.

post_text:
Carteret County Emergency Management will partner with the National Weather Service in Newport to conduct a Virtual Hurricane Community Forum for Carteret County residents. The forum will take place on Wednesday, September 9, beginning at 6:30 pm. The forum will discuss important information on personal preparedness actions and updates on weather service forecast products. Topics will include adapting preparedness efforts to meet the challenges presented by COVID-19 and why it’s important to never just focus on the category of a storm, but instead focus on the possible impacts. Attendees will also have the opportunity to ask questions.
Register for the virtual forum here: https://attendee.gotowebinar.com/register/3392001477585403918

post_text: Carteret County Public School System hosted several state leaders yesterday. These leaders visited with Superintendent Dr. Rob Jackson and school system leaders to learn more about the school system's opening this year. Visitors included Senator Norman Sanderson, Representative Craig Horn, Representative Ashton Clemmons and State Board of Education Legislative Director Freebird McKinney. The visitors toured Beaufort Elementary School, Beaufort Middle School and East Carteret High School and were joined throughout the morning by Board of Education Chair John McLean, Vice Chair Clark Jenkins, and members Kathryn Chadwick and Brittany Wheatly.

post_text: The Carteret County Public School System relies on the outstanding men and women who serve as teachers, staff, and administrators in our schools. Without their service, the system would be unable to provide the high-quality educational opportunities for students that the community has come to expect. Many of the school system employees have school-aged children. They, like many other parents, are struggling to find child care for their school-aged children while they are working. In order for the school system to continue to operate at the high-level expected, these employees have been offered the opportunity to have their children attend face-to-face instruction four days a week. This is an effort to keep school system employees teaching and working so that every child in the county may continue to be served. Every member of the school system staff looks forward to having every student attend school in person full-time as soon as we are allowed to by the Governor.

post_text: Stuff the Bus ... Free school supplies will be distributed Wednesday, August 5, from 8 to 11 a.m. in front of the former KMart Store in Morehead City. Bookbags have been packed with school supplies and will given out to Carteret County Public School System students while supplies last. This will be a drive-through distribution with volunteers handing out bookbags. Drivers will remain in their vehicles and will circle through the parking lot as directed. This event is sponsored by Parkview Baptist Church, Ann Street Methodist Church, Parkview Baptist Kids - VBS/Day Camp, the Carteret County Public School Foundation, Willis Insurance Agency of Beaufort and numerous individual donors. #carteretstrong

post_text:
Carteret County Board of Education members voted to implement Plan B as presented with a review of additional square footage data of classrooms as soon as it is available.
Dr. Rob Jackson recommended on behalf of the school system administration and the re-entry committees that the Board of Education implement Plan B in which students alternate in-person days within each week of school. All students, pre-kindergarten through 12th grade, will be assigned a cohort (A or B) which will attend school in-person two days each week and learn remotely three days each week, on an alternating basis.
Complete details of this plan will be finalized based on today’s action by the Board of Education. This will take place as quickly as possible and a Parent Guide will be available soon, along with a number of informational videos.

A 100% virtual option will also be available for any family that chooses it for their student.

Families with children in multiple schools will be on the same cohort. (ie. elementary student on cohort A, middle and/or high school student will also be on cohort A)

Cory Johnson will serve as the principal of the MaST Early College High School. The announcement was made this morning by Superintendent Dr. Rob Jackson. Mr. Johnson will begin his duties July 21 and will fill the role left vacant when former MaST principal Deanne Rosen resigned.
Mr. Johnson has been serving as an assistant principal at Fort Mill High School in South Carolina and was previously an assistant principal at Fort Mill Middle School. He also taught US History, Government and Economics at the high school level.

post_text: Join in a special recognition of Carteret County's Spring Sports Senior Athletes this Friday at 8:20 p.m. The outside athletic field lights will be turned on for 20 minutes at our three high schools - Croatan High School, East Carteret High School and West Carteret High School. From 8:20 p.m. to 8:40 p.m. the lights will be bright to honor the Spring Sports Seniors and their families who lost their season because of COVID-19. If you would like to drive by the school please follow the traffic directions each school has set and please stay in your vehicle. If you are staying at home, turn on your outside porch lights during that same time frame. #supportingourstudents

post_text: The Carteret County Public School System employees continue to prepare and deliver meals to young people in the county. Last week 20,028 meals were provided. Our dedicated Child Nutrition employees, teacher assistants/bus drivers and many others are providing this service and it is greatly needed and appreciated. Anyone under the age of 18 can receive free meals. If your children have not received meals and you would like them to receive the meals you can either go to one of the six school sites between 11 a.m. and 1 p.m. to pick up meals or you can call one of those sites and ask that meals be delivered to your home. The six school sites are Beaufort Middle, Bogue Sound Elementary, Down East Middle, Morehead City Primary, Newport Elementary and White Oak Elementary.

post_text: As many of you are aware, Governor Cooper ordered all NC Public Schools closed starting Monday, March 16 for a period of at least two weeks. Beginning, Monday, March 16, 2020, there will be no school for students until further notice. Monday will be a mandatory workday for all staff members. Students will be allowed to come pick up personal items from 8 a.m. to 3 p.m. on Monday. We understand you may have many more questions, as do we. We are working with our Child Nutrition leaders to coordinate a plan for making meals available for our students during this time. We will continue to update you.

post_text: Congratulations to Sarah Prosser of West Carteret High School. She is a 2020 Morehead-Cain Scholar. The Morehead-Cain Scholarship was the first merit scholarship program established in the United States and founded at UNC-Chapel Hill. The scholarship was named for its benefactors, John Motley Morehead III and the Gordon and Mary Cain Foundation.

post_text:
The 2020 Brad Sneeden Marine Science Academy will take place June 22-26, 2020, and is designed for rising seventh, eighth and ninth graders. Fifty students from the Carteret County Public School System and 10 students from the Craven County Public School System will be accepted into the program this year. Students who previously participated in the Academy are welcome to apply for acceptance again this year.
Applications are posted online at www.carteretcountyschools.org and can be found on the right side of the front page. Applications are also available at schools in Carteret County with middle school grades. Applications are due April 22.

post_text: There is a power outage on Hwy 24 the is impacting Broad Creek Middle School. It is the result of a traffic accident. Carteret-Craven EMC crews are working quickly and expect to have the power restored by 6:45ish. Morning school schedules will remain the same. If you live in an area impacted by the power outage, please try to get to school and be safe. This could impact students who live in the area and attend Bogue Sound Elementary, Broad Creek Middle, Croatan High and the Newport schools.

post_text: Kent Pittman is one of three finalists for the Southeast Region Beginning Teacher of the Year award. He will travel to Cullowee in December for interviews to determine the overall Beginning Teacher of the Year. Mr. Pittman is an English teacher at MaST Early College High School. He is a native of Beaufort and a graduate of East Carteret High School. Mr. Pittman holds a bachelor’s degree in communications and journalism and a master’s degree in teaching secondary English. Mr. Pittman completed his student teaching at East Carteret High School and then joined the staff at MaST last year.

post_text: Carteret County Public School System's Finance Department again received two top financial awards and several members of the Department attended tonight's Board of Education meeting to receive the awards. The awards are for the Comprehensive Annual Financial Report. The school system received a Certificate of Excellence in Financial Reporting from the Association of School Business Officials (ASBO) International. The department also received the Certificate of Achievement for Excellence in Financial Reporting from the Government Finance Officers Association (GFOA) of the United States and Canada. Pictured, from the left, are Benefits Specialist Kim Guyton, Accounts Payable Assistant Serina Kannon, Senior Accountant Casey Harris, Deputy Finance Officer Julie Bernotski and Chief Financial Officer Kathy Carswell. Superintendent Mat Bottoms and Assistant Superintendent Blair Propst, pictured far right, shared information about the awards and congratulated the department members.

Lindsey Howell is one of two finalists for the title of Southeast Region Teacher of the Year. The announcement was made today and comes after the first round of interviews with each of the 12 county Teachers of the Year in the Southeast Region.
A finalist selection committee will meet with Mrs. Howell in the coming weeks for on-site interviews, and then the Southeast Region Teacher of the Year will be announced. The Regional Teachers of the Year from the nine regions of the state advance to the state level.
Mrs. Howell is a history teacher and a coach at West Carteret High School. She joined the West Carteret High School staff in 2007 after teaching in Tennessee.
Mrs. Howell is Carteret County’s 2019-2020 Teacher of the Year. This award is sponsored by Chick-fil-a of Morehead City. As the county’s winner, Mrs. Howell received the free use of a vehicle from Kurtis Chevrolet of Morehead City.
